SIMPLE: scanty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scanty
<hw>Scant"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Scantier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Scantiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[From <er>Scant</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lacking amplitude or extent;
narrow; small; not abundant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His dominions were very narrow and <qex>scanty</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>scantier</qex> limits the proud arch confine.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Somewhat less than is needed; insufficient; scant;
<as>as, a <ex>scanty</ex> supply of words; a <ex>scanty</ex> supply of
bread</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sparing; niggardly; parsimonious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In illustrating a point of difficulty, be not too
<qex>scanty</qex> of words.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Scant; narrow; small; poor; deficient; meager;
scarce; chary; sparing; parsimonious; penurious; niggardly;
grudging.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scape</ent>⟦br⟧
